Below is a **self‑contained example** that shows a C++ class with a user‑defined constructor and destructor.  
The class (`Buffer`) allocates a dynamic array in its constructor and releases it in the destructor – a classic RAII (Resource‑Acquisition‑Is‑Initialization) pattern.  
The example also includes a small `main()` program that demonstrates the class in action.

```cpp
/********************************************************************
 *  Buffer.hpp
 *
 *  A tiny class that owns a dynamically‑allocated character buffer.
 *  It prints messages when the constructor and destructor run so you
 *  can see the lifetime of the object.
 ********************************************************************/
#ifndef BUFFER_HPP
#define BUFFER_HPP

#include <cstddef>   // std::size_t
#include <iostream>
#include <algorithm> // std::copy_n
#include <cstring>   // std::strlen

class Buffer
{
public:
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    //  Constructor
    //  Takes an optional C‑string to initialise the internal buffer.
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    explicit Buffer(const char* init = nullptr)
        : m_size(0), m_data(nullptr)
    {
        std::cout << "[Buffer] Constructor called.\n";

        if (init) {
            m_size = std::strlen(init);
            m_data = new char[m_size + 1];          // +1 for the terminating '\0'
            std::copy_n(init, m_size + 1, m_data); // copy including '\0'
        } else {
            // Allocate a default empty buffer (size 0, but still a valid pointer)
            m_data = new char[1];
            m_data[0] = '\0';
        }

        std::cout << "  -> allocated " << m_size << " byte(s).\n";
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    //  Destructor
    //  Releases the memory that was acquired in the constructor.
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    ~Buffer()
    {
        std::cout << "[Buffer] Destructor called.\n";
        std::cout << "  -> releasing " << m_size << " byte(s).\n";

        delete[] m_data;   // safe even if m_data == nullptr
        m_data = nullptr;
        m_size = 0;
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    //  Deleted copy operations – the class is non‑copyable.
    //  (You could implement them, but for this demo we keep it simple.)
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    Buffer(const Buffer&)            = delete;
    Buffer& operator=(const Buffer&) = delete;

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    //  Move operations – allow transfer of ownership.
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    Buffer(Buffer&& other) noexcept
        : m_size(other.m_size), m_data(other.m_data)
    {
        std::cout << "[Buffer] Move constructor called.\n";
        other.m_data = nullptr;
        other.m_size = 0;
    }

    Buffer& operator=(Buffer&& other) noexcept
    {
        std::cout << "[Buffer] Move assignment operator called.\n";
        if (this != &other) {
            delete[] m_data;               // free current resource
            m_data = other.m_data;
            m_size = other.m_size;

            other.m_data = nullptr;
            other.m_size = 0;
        }
        return *this;
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    //  Simple accessor
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    const char* data() const noexcept { return m_data; }
    std::size_t size() const noexcept { return m_size; }

private:
    std::size_t m_size; // number of characters *excluding* the terminating '\0'
    char*       m_data; // owned heap memory
};

#endif // BUFFER_HPP
```

```cpp
/********************************************************************
 *  main.cpp
 *
 *  Demonstrates the Buffer class.
 ********************************************************************/
#include "Buffer.hpp"

int main()
{
    std::cout << "=== Creating a Buffer with an initial string ===\n";
    Buffer b1("Hello, world!");          // ctor allocates & copies the string
    std::cout << "b1 holds: \"" << b1.data() << "\"\n\n";

    std::cout << "=== Moving b1 into b2 ===\n";
    Buffer b2(std::move(b1));            // move ctor transfers ownership
    std::cout << "b2 now holds: \"" << b2.data() << "\"\n";
    std::cout << "b1 after move holds: \"" << (b1.data() ? b1.data() : "null") << "\"\n\n";

    std::cout << "=== Leaving scope, destructors will run ===\n";
    return 0; // b2 (and then b1) are destroyed automatically
}
```

### What you see when you run it

```
=== Creating a Buffer with an initial string ===
[Buffer] Constructor called.
  -> allocated 13 byte(s).
b1 holds: "Hello, world!"

=== Moving b1 into b2 ===
[Buffer] Move constructor called.
b2 now holds: "Hello, world!"
b1 after move holds: ""

=== Leaving scope, destructors will run ===
[Buffer] Destructor called.
  -> releasing 13 byte(s).
[Buffer] Destructor called.
  -> releasing 0 byte(s).
```

### Key points illustrated

| Feature | Why it matters |
|---------|----------------|
| **Constructor** (`explicit Buffer(const char* init = nullptr)`) | Acquires a resource (dynamic memory) and puts the object into a valid state. |
| **Destructor** (`~Buffer()`) | Guarantees the resource is released, preventing leaks. |
| **RAII** | The lifetime of the resource is bound to the lifetime of the object – no manual `delete` needed elsewhere. |
| **Deleted copy operations** | Prevent accidental shallow copies that would double‑free the same memory. |
| **Move semantics** | Allows efficient transfer of ownership without copying the buffer. |
| **`explicit`** | Stops implicit conversions from `const char*` to `Buffer`. |
| **`noexcept`** on move operations | Lets the standard library use the move constructor/assignment in containers safely. |

Feel free to adapt the class (add copy semantics, more methods, etc.) for your own project – the skeleton above already gives you a clean, well‑behaved C++ class with a constructor and destructor. Happy coding!

Here’s a minimal, self‑contained example that shows a **for‑each** (enhanced for) loop iterating over a `java.util.List`.  
Feel free to copy‑paste it into any class or a `main` method.

```java
import java.util.List;
import java.util.ArrayList;

public class ForEachDemo {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // 1️⃣ Create and populate a List (of Strings in this case)
        List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();
        names.add("Alice");
        names.add("Bob");
        names.add("Charlie");

        // 2️⃣ Iterate over the list with a for‑each loop
        for (String name : names) {
            // Inside the loop, 'name' holds the current element
            System.out.println("Hello, " + name + "!");
        }
    }
}
```

### What’s happening?

| Part | Meaning |
|------|----------|
| `for (String name : names)` | The **enhanced for** syntax. It reads “for each `String` element in `names`”. |
| `String name` | The loop variable that receives the current element on each iteration. |
| `names` | The `Iterable` (any `Collection`, array, etc.) you’re looping over. |
| Body (`System.out.println…`) | Code executed once per element. |

### Variations

* **Different element type** – just change the generic type and loop variable:

  ```java
  List<Integer> numbers = List.of(1, 2, 3);
  for (int n : numbers) {
      System.out.println(n * n);
  }
  ```

* **Using an interface type** – you can iterate over any `Iterable<T>` (e.g., `Set`, `Queue`, custom collections):

  ```java
  Iterable<Double> values = List.of(3.14, 2.71);
  for (Double d : values) {
      System.out.println(d);
  }
  ```

* **Read‑only vs. mutable** – The loop variable is a **copy** of the reference, not the collection itself.  
  Modifying the element (if it’s mutable) will affect the list, but reassigning the loop variable won’t:

  ```java
  List<StringBuilder> builders = List.of(new StringBuilder("a"), new StringBuilder("b"));
  for (StringBuilder sb : builders) {
      sb.append("!");          // modifies the objects inside the list
      // sb = new StringBuilder(); // this would NOT replace the list entry
  }
  ```

That’s all you need to iterate over a list with a Java for‑each loop! 🚀
